./docs/sprint-memos/7h-40-V5d-operator-bootstrap.codex.log:5606:docs/sprint-memos/7h-39-V4-regex-memo.codex.log:513:/Users/martin/Downloads/JOURNAL.md:1644:- `LESSONS.md` new entry `[daybook][regex-by-reference-inflation]` 2026-04-27: explains the substring-match ghost-debt accumulation pattern; recommends regex tightening in `agent_review_loop.py` (line-anchor on checkbox or section header) as long-term fix.
./docs/sprint-memos/7h-40-V5d-operator-bootstrap.codex.log:5607:docs/sprint-memos/7h-39-V4-regex-memo.codex.log:516:/Users/martin/Downloads/LESSONS.md:383:- 2026-04-26 [enforcement][trend-watch] **Auto-review can detect rotting-pending by reading prior archives; one-shot session metrics miss the slow-growing failure modes.** `agent_review_loop.py` `audit_daybook` now reads the prior 2 entries from `review-archive/` (cheap regex extraction of `pending_journal_items: N` from the markdown), builds a 1-3 element `pending_trend`, and the recommender fires hard `DAYBOOK:` alert when the trend is non-decreasing. Why this matters: a single session with `pending=12` looks indistinguishable from a healthy session that just happens to have queue work; three consecutive sessions with `pending` ≥ each prior is the rot signal. Pattern: per-session metric thresholds catch acute drift; cross-session trends catch chronic drift. Both axes needed — rely on either alone and the other slips.
./docs/sprint-memos/7h-40-V5d-operator-bootstrap.codex.log:5608:docs/sprint-memos/7h-39-V4-regex-memo.codex.log:517:/Users/martin/Downloads/LESSONS.md:412:- 2026-04-27 [daybook][regex-by-reference-inflation] **`pending_journal_items` regex (`agent_review_loop.py`: `^[-*]\s*\[\s\]` OR `"Pending decisions" in line`) double-counts every JOURNAL line that *references* the WORKTREES.md "Pending decisions" section, even when the referenced rows are DONE.** Sprint 7h-30 review fired sticky DAYBOOK alert (`pending_trend=[6,6,6]`) but 5 of 6 hits were historical sprint carry-over notes pointing at items 1-5 (closed in 7h-6); only 3 truly-open items remained in WORKTREES.md (#6 KSM live-proof, #7 bus.py cov, #8 cov ratchet 84→85). Fix applied in 7h-31: rephrase historical refs from `"Pending decisions"` (quoted) to `worktree-followups` (unquoted, regex-defanged) + `_[CLOSED 7h-6]_` suffix; pending count drops 6 → 0 honestly. Pattern: substring-match counters over append-only logs accumulate ghost-debt because closed items' textual references survive the closure event. Two structural mitigations: (A) regex requires line to start with checkbox or section header, not arbitrary in-line phrase, (B) close-out events rewrite the referenced phrase to a different token. Applied B for cheapness; A is the cleaner long-term fix in `agent_review_loop.py`.
./docs/sprint-memos/7h-40-V5d-operator-bootstrap.codex.log:5609:docs/sprint-memos/7h-39-V4-regex-memo.codex.log:518:/Users/martin/Downloads/LESSONS.md:424:- 2026-04-27 [orchestration][branch-cleanup-after-parent-merge] **After parent-merge (`--no-ff`) of two sibling worker branches, delete local + origin branches AND `git worktree remove` in the same sprint.** Otherwise `git worktree list` keeps stale linked worktrees that confuse next-sprint `git worktree add -b cursor/<name>` (it errors "already a worktree" or reuses stale branch state). Sequence after merge-to-main + push: `git worktree remove ../<linked>` (×N), `git branch -d cursor/<name>` (×N), `git push origin --delete cursor/<name>` (×N). Verify with `git worktree list` and `git ls-remote origin 'cursor/*'`. Skipping this leaves bookkeeping debt and inflates `pending_journal_items` over time as branches accumulate.
./docs/sprint-memos/7h-40-V5d-operator-bootstrap.codex.log:5610:docs/sprint-memos/7h-39-V4-regex-memo.codex.log:540:/Users/martin/.cursor-daybook-sync/LESSONS.md:383:- 2026-04-26 [enforcement][trend-watch] **Auto-review can detect rotting-pending by reading prior archives; one-shot session metrics miss the slow-growing failure modes.** `agent_review_loop.py` `audit_daybook` now reads the prior 2 entries from `review-archive/` (cheap regex extraction of `pending_journal_items: N` from the markdown), builds a 1-3 element `pending_trend`, and the recommender fires hard `DAYBOOK:` alert when the trend is non-decreasing. Why this matters: a single session with `pending=12` looks indistinguishable from a healthy session that just happens to have queue work; three consecutive sessions with `pending` ≥ each prior is the rot signal. Pattern: per-session metric thresholds catch acute drift; cross-session trends catch chronic drift. Both axes needed — rely on either alone and the other slips.
./docs/sprint-memos/7h-40-V5d-operator-bootstrap.codex.log:5611:docs/sprint-memos/7h-39-V4-regex-memo.codex.log:541:/Users/martin/.cursor-daybook-sync/LESSONS.md:412:- 2026-04-27 [daybook][regex-by-reference-inflation] **`pending_journal_items` regex (`agent_review_loop.py`: `^[-*]\s*\[\s\]` OR `"Pending decisions" in line`) double-counts every JOURNAL line that *references* the WORKTREES.md "Pending decisions" section, even when the referenced rows are DONE.** Sprint 7h-30 review fired sticky DAYBOOK alert (`pending_trend=[6,6,6]`) but 5 of 6 hits were historical sprint carry-over notes pointing at items 1-5 (closed in 7h-6); only 3 truly-open items remained in WORKTREES.md (#6 KSM live-proof, #7 bus.py cov, #8 cov ratchet 84→85). Fix applied in 7h-31: rephrase historical refs from `"Pending decisions"` (quoted) to `worktree-followups` (unquoted, regex-defanged) + `_[CLOSED 7h-6]_` suffix; pending count drops 6 → 0 honestly. Pattern: substring-match counters over append-only logs accumulate ghost-debt because closed items' textual references survive the closure event. Two structural mitigations: (A) regex requires line to start with checkbox or section header, not arbitrary in-line phrase, (B) close-out events rewrite the referenced phrase to a different token. Applied B for cheapness; A is the cleaner long-term fix in `agent_review_loop.py`.
./docs/sprint-memos/7h-40-V5d-operator-bootstrap.codex.log:5612:docs/sprint-memos/7h-39-V4-regex-memo.codex.log:542:/Users/martin/.cursor-daybook-sync/LESSONS.md:424:- 2026-04-27 [orchestration][branch-cleanup-after-parent-merge] **After parent-merge (`--no-ff`) of two sibling worker branches, delete local + origin branches AND `git worktree remove` in the same sprint.** Otherwise `git worktree list` keeps stale linked worktrees that confuse next-sprint `git worktree add -b cursor/<name>` (it errors "already a worktree" or reuses stale branch state). Sequence after merge-to-main + push: `git worktree remove ../<linked>` (×N), `git branch -d cursor/<name>` (×N), `git push origin --delete cursor/<name>` (×N). Verify with `git worktree list` and `git ls-remote origin 'cursor/*'`. Skipping this leaves bookkeeping debt and inflates `pending_journal_items` over time as branches accumulate.
./docs/sprint-memos/7h-40-V5d-operator-bootstrap.codex.log:5613:docs/sprint-memos/7h-39-V4-regex-memo.codex.log:543:/Users/martin/.cursor-daybook-sync/LESSONS.md.bak:383:- 2026-04-26 [enforcement][trend-watch] **Auto-review can detect rotting-pending by reading prior archives; one-shot session metrics miss the slow-growing failure modes.** `agent_review_loop.py` `audit_daybook` now reads the prior 2 entries from `review-archive/` (cheap regex extraction of `pending_journal_items: N` from the markdown), builds a 1-3 element `pending_trend`, and the recommender fires hard `DAYBOOK:` alert when the trend is non-decreasing. Why this matters: a single session with `pending=12` looks indistinguishable from a healthy session that just happens to have queue work; three consecutive sessions with `pending` ≥ each prior is the rot signal. Pattern: per-session metric thresholds catch acute drift; cross-session trends catch chronic drift. Both axes needed — rely on either alone and the other slips.
./docs/sprint-memos/7h-40-V5d-operator-bootstrap.codex.log:5614:docs/sprint-memos/7h-39-V4-regex-memo.codex.log:561:/Users/martin/.cursor-daybook-sync/LESSONS.md:176:- 2026-04-26 [context-opt][batch-knobs] **Context-optimisation is most effective as a batched "small-knob sweep" not as one-off tweaks per sprint.** Sprint 7h-12 batch: BLOAT 4000→3000 + boot-head 50→30 + boot-tail 40→25 + journal_archive helper landed together. Each individual knob is trivially small but the cumulative effect across a session is meaningful (~30% reduction in boot/sticky bytes). Pattern: every ~5 sprints, sweep `score_latest_reply.py`, `agent_session_boot.sh`, `prompt_resume_guard.sh`, `agent_review_loop.py`, daybook archive helpers as a single batch. Cheaper than reasoning about each in isolation; lets the parent see the cumulative envelope.
./docs/sprint-memos/7h-40-V5d-operator-bootstrap.codex.log:5615:docs/sprint-memos/7h-39-V4-regex-memo.codex.log:562:/Users/martin/.cursor-daybook-sync/LESSONS.md:325:- 2026-04-26 [discipline][self-tuning] **The discipline closes the loop only when measurement runs without agent cooperation AND results inherit forward.** Sprint 7b/7c added gates that the agent must remember to call (`agent_pre_claim.sh`, `agent_session_boot.sh`). 7d adds `agent_review_loop.py` fired by the `stop` hook (no agent action) writing `~/.cursor/hooks-log/review-latest.md`, which session N+1's `agent_session_boot.sh` heads at the top of boot output (no agent action). Pattern: any review system that depends on the reviewee remembering to review will decay. Either the review is automated (telemetry → digest) AND the digest is forced into the next session's first-screen context, or the review is theatre. Both halves required.
./docs/sprint-memos/7h-40-V5d-operator-bootstrap.codex.log:5616:docs/sprint-memos/7h-39-V4-regex-memo.codex.log:563:/Users/martin/.cursor-daybook-sync/LESSONS.md:328:- 2026-04-26 [hooks][async] **`stop` hook can run informational scripts (pre-claim, review) without blocking — exit 0 immediately, write to disk, next session reads.** Previously the only hook-output surface I knew was the immediate one (sessionStart `additional_context`, beforeShellExecution `permission`). For `stop` hook, the surface is "next session reads disk" — the hook writes `review-latest.md` and `agent_session_boot.sh` heads it on next boot. This pattern unlocks: any session-end audit that wants to influence the next session. Generalises: write to a known location, have the boot wrapper read it.
./docs/sprint-memos/7h-40-V5d-operator-bootstrap.codex.log:5617:docs/sprint-memos/7h-39-V4-regex-memo.codex.log:564:/Users/martin/.cursor-daybook-sync/LESSONS.md:340:- 2026-04-26 [auto-review][sticky-alert] **Acknowledging an auto-review alert in chat is not the fix; the alert must keep injecting until the metric heals.** Sprint 7d auto-review surfaced PROSE density 18.54% > 12% threshold; agent (me) replied "re-pinning caveman" and kept writing prose. Behavioural fix proven unreliable in same reply that names the problem. Structural fix in `prompt_resume_guard.sh` (Sprint 7g): hard-severity recs (PROSE / BLOAT / ORCHESTRATION / BOOT / DAYBOOK prefixes in `review-latest.json`) inject as `user_message` on EVERY prompt until next `stop` hook's auto-review clears them. Resume-class prompts get alerts + full boot dump; non-resume prompts get alerts-only short note. No alerts → clean passthrough, zero noise. Pattern: every monitoring signal needs a "stays-on-until-cleared" injection path, not just a one-shot reminder.
./docs/sprint-memos/7h-40-V5d-operator-bootstrap.codex.log:5618:docs/sprint-memos/7h-39-V4-regex-memo.codex.log:565:/Users/martin/.cursor-daybook-sync/LESSONS.md:372:- 2026-04-26 [auto-review][post-hoc-only][closed] **Mid-session prose-density gate via `score_latest_reply.py` integrated into `agent_pre_claim.sh` closes the gap that `agent_review_loop.py` only measures at session-stop.** Sprint 7h-10 wired the scorer to read the live transcript's most-recent assistant turn, strip code fences/inline code, count prose tokens (the/a/just/...) per total words, exit non-zero ≥12% density (matches token-economy.mdc threshold) OR ≥4000 chars (`REPLY_CHAR_BLOAT`). Gate validation: first run reported "no assistant turn yet" because the scorer didn't drill into Cursor's `{role: assistant, message: {content: [{type:text, text:"..."}]}}` envelope; fixed to always check `obj["message"]` if present. Live re-run on the prior reply: density 8.45% (clean) but chars=4935 → BLOAT triggered. Density-clean ≠ short — both axes needed. Pattern: any post-hoc measurement loop also needs a pre-claim gate that reads the same live signal; the loop's job is trend, the gate's job is THIS reply.
./docs/sprint-memos/7h-40-V5d-operator-bootstrap.codex.log:5619:docs/sprint-memos/7h-39-V4-regex-memo.codex.log:566:/Users/martin/.cursor-daybook-sync/LESSONS.md:381:- 2026-04-26 [enforcement][sticky-via-prefix] **Adding a new `<PREFIX>:` to `prompt_resume_guard.sh`'s `hard_prefixes` tuple is the cheapest way to convert an advisory log entry into a sticky-until-cleared user-visible alert.** Sprint 7h-13: `pre_claim_stop.sh` now injects `PRECLAIM:` recommendations into `review-latest.json` when `agent_pre_claim.sh` exits non-zero; one-line addition `"PRECLAIM:"` to `hard_prefixes` propagates the existing fingerprint→sticky→compact-after-N machinery to the new alert class. No new state file, no new injection path, no new compaction logic. Pattern: when a new failure mode needs sticky enforcement, prefer extending the existing alert-prefix taxonomy over inventing a parallel mechanism — the cost is one tuple entry + one upstream injector that emits with the prefix. Existing taxonomy now: PROSE, BLOAT, ORCHESTRATION, BOOT, DAYBOOK, PRECLAIM.
./docs/sprint-memos/7h-40-V5d-operator-bootstrap.codex.log:5620:docs/sprint-memos/7h-39-V4-regex-memo.codex.log:567:/Users/martin/.cursor-daybook-sync/LESSONS.md:383:- 2026-04-26 [enforcement][trend-watch] **Auto-review can detect rotting-pending by reading prior archives; one-shot session metrics miss the slow-growing failure modes.** `agent_review_loop.py` `audit_daybook` now reads the prior 2 entries from `review-archive/` (cheap regex extraction of `pending_journal_items: N` from the markdown), builds a 1-3 element `pending_trend`, and the recommender fires hard `DAYBOOK:` alert when the trend is non-decreasing. Why this matters: a single session with `pending=12` looks indistinguishable from a healthy session that just happens to have queue work; three consecutive sessions with `pending` ≥ each prior is the rot signal. Pattern: per-session metric thresholds catch acute drift; cross-session trends catch chronic drift. Both axes needed — rely on either alone and the other slips.
./docs/sprint-memos/7h-40-V5d-operator-bootstrap.codex.log:5621:docs/sprint-memos/7h-39-V4-regex-memo.codex.log:568:/Users/martin/.cursor-daybook-sync/LESSONS.md:412:- 2026-04-27 [daybook][regex-by-reference-inflation] **`pending_journal_items` regex (`agent_review_loop.py`: `^[-*]\s*\[\s\]` OR `"Pending decisions" in line`) double-counts every JOURNAL line that *references* the WORKTREES.md "Pending decisions" section, even when the referenced rows are DONE.** Sprint 7h-30 review fired sticky DAYBOOK alert (`pending_trend=[6,6,6]`) but 5 of 6 hits were historical sprint carry-over notes pointing at items 1-5 (closed in 7h-6); only 3 truly-open items remained in WORKTREES.md (#6 KSM live-proof, #7 bus.py cov, #8 cov ratchet 84→85). Fix applied in 7h-31: rephrase historical refs from `"Pending decisions"` (quoted) to `worktree-followups` (unquoted, regex-defanged) + `_[CLOSED 7h-6]_` suffix; pending count drops 6 → 0 honestly. Pattern: substring-match counters over append-only logs accumulate ghost-debt because closed items' textual references survive the closure event. Two structural mitigations: (A) regex requires line to start with checkbox or section header, not arbitrary in-line phrase, (B) close-out events rewrite the referenced phrase to a different token. Applied B for cheapness; A is the cleaner long-term fix in `agent_review_loop.py`.
./docs/sprint-memos/7h-40-V5d-operator-bootstrap.codex.log:5622:docs/sprint-memos/7h-39-V4-regex-memo.codex.log:569:/Users/martin/.cursor-daybook-sync/LESSONS.md:424:- 2026-04-27 [orchestration][branch-cleanup-after-parent-merge] **After parent-merge (`--no-ff`) of two sibling worker branches, delete local + origin branches AND `git worktree remove` in the same sprint.** Otherwise `git worktree list` keeps stale linked worktrees that confuse next-sprint `git worktree add -b cursor/<name>` (it errors "already a worktree" or reuses stale branch state). Sequence after merge-to-main + push: `git worktree remove ../<linked>` (×N), `git branch -d cursor/<name>` (×N), `git push origin --delete cursor/<name>` (×N). Verify with `git worktree list` and `git ls-remote origin 'cursor/*'`. Skipping this leaves bookkeeping debt and inflates `pending_journal_items` over time as branches accumulate.
./docs/sprint-memos/7h-40-V5d-operator-bootstrap.codex.log:5623:docs/sprint-memos/7h-39-V4-regex-memo.codex.log:570:/Users/martin/.cursor-daybook-sync/LESSONS.md.bak:176:- 2026-04-26 [context-opt][batch-knobs] **Context-optimisation is most effective as a batched "small-knob sweep" not as one-off tweaks per sprint.** Sprint 7h-12 batch: BLOAT 4000→3000 + boot-head 50→30 + boot-tail 40→25 + journal_archive helper landed together. Each individual knob is trivially small but the cumulative effect across a session is meaningful (~30% reduction in boot/sticky bytes). Pattern: every ~5 sprints, sweep `score_latest_reply.py`, `agent_session_boot.sh`, `prompt_resume_guard.sh`, `agent_review_loop.py`, daybook archive helpers as a single batch. Cheaper than reasoning about each in isolation; lets the parent see the cumulative envelope.
./docs/sprint-memos/7h-40-V5d-operator-bootstrap.codex.log:5624:docs/sprint-memos/7h-39-V4-regex-memo.codex.log:571:/Users/martin/.cursor-daybook-sync/LESSONS.md.bak:325:- 2026-04-26 [discipline][self-tuning] **The discipline closes the loop only when measurement runs without agent cooperation AND results inherit forward.** Sprint 7b/7c added gates that the agent must remember to call (`agent_pre_claim.sh`, `agent_session_boot.sh`). 7d adds `agent_review_loop.py` fired by the `stop` hook (no agent action) writing `~/.cursor/hooks-log/review-latest.md`, which session N+1's `agent_session_boot.sh` heads at the top of boot output (no agent action). Pattern: any review system that depends on the reviewee remembering to review will decay. Either the review is automated (telemetry → digest) AND the digest is forced into the next session's first-screen context, or the review is theatre. Both halves required.
./docs/sprint-memos/7h-40-V5d-operator-bootstrap.codex.log:5625:docs/sprint-memos/7h-39-V4-regex-memo.codex.log:572:/Users/martin/.cursor-daybook-sync/LESSONS.md.bak:328:- 2026-04-26 [hooks][async] **`stop` hook can run informational scripts (pre-claim, review) without blocking — exit 0 immediately, write to disk, next session reads.** Previously the only hook-output surface I knew was the immediate one (sessionStart `additional_context`, beforeShellExecution `permission`). For `stop` hook, the surface is "next session reads disk" — the hook writes `review-latest.md` and `agent_session_boot.sh` heads it on next boot. This pattern unlocks: any session-end audit that wants to influence the next session. Generalises: write to a known location, have the boot wrapper read it.
./docs/sprint-memos/7h-40-V5d-operator-bootstrap.codex.log:5626:docs/sprint-memos/7h-39-V4-regex-memo.codex.log:573:/Users/martin/.cursor-daybook-sync/LESSONS.md.bak:340:- 2026-04-26 [auto-review][sticky-alert] **Acknowledging an auto-review alert in chat is not the fix; the alert must keep injecting until the metric heals.** Sprint 7d auto-review surfaced PROSE density 18.54% > 12% threshold; agent (me) replied "re-pinning caveman" and kept writing prose. Behavioural fix proven unreliable in same reply that names the problem. Structural fix in `prompt_resume_guard.sh` (Sprint 7g): hard-severity recs (PROSE / BLOAT / ORCHESTRATION / BOOT / DAYBOOK prefixes in `review-latest.json`) inject as `user_message` on EVERY prompt until next `stop` hook's auto-review clears them. Resume-class prompts get alerts + full boot dump; non-resume prompts get alerts-only short note. No alerts → clean passthrough, zero noise. Pattern: every monitoring signal needs a "stays-on-until-cleared" injection path, not just a one-shot reminder.
./docs/sprint-memos/7h-40-V5d-operator-bootstrap.codex.log:5627:docs/sprint-memos/7h-39-V4-regex-memo.codex.log:574:/Users/martin/.cursor-daybook-sync/LESSONS.md.bak:372:- 2026-04-26 [auto-review][post-hoc-only][closed] **Mid-session prose-density gate via `score_latest_reply.py` integrated into `agent_pre_claim.sh` closes the gap that `agent_review_loop.py` only measures at session-stop.** Sprint 7h-10 wired the scorer to read the live transcript's most-recent assistant turn, strip code fences/inline code, count prose tokens (the/a/just/...) per total words, exit non-zero ≥12% density (matches token-economy.mdc threshold) OR ≥4000 chars (`REPLY_CHAR_BLOAT`). Gate validation: first run reported "no assistant turn yet" because the scorer didn't drill into Cursor's `{role: assistant, message: {content: [{type:text, text:"..."}]}}` envelope; fixed to always check `obj["message"]` if present. Live re-run on the prior reply: density 8.45% (clean) but chars=4935 → BLOAT triggered. Density-clean ≠ short — both axes needed. Pattern: any post-hoc measurement loop also needs a pre-claim gate that reads the same live signal; the loop's job is trend, the gate's job is THIS reply.
./docs/sprint-memos/7h-40-V5d-operator-bootstrap.codex.log:5628:docs/sprint-memos/7h-39-V4-regex-memo.codex.log:575:/Users/martin/.cursor-daybook-sync/LESSONS.md.bak:381:- 2026-04-26 [enforcement][sticky-via-prefix] **Adding a new `<PREFIX>:` to `prompt_resume_guard.sh`'s `hard_prefixes` tuple is the cheapest way to convert an advisory log entry into a sticky-until-cleared user-visible alert.** Sprint 7h-13: `pre_claim_stop.sh` now injects `PRECLAIM:` recommendations into `review-latest.json` when `agent_pre_claim.sh` exits non-zero; one-line addition `"PRECLAIM:"` to `hard_prefixes` propagates the existing fingerprint→sticky→compact-after-N machinery to the new alert class. No new state file, no new injection path, no new compaction logic. Pattern: when a new failure mode needs sticky enforcement, prefer extending the existing alert-prefix taxonomy over inventing a parallel mechanism — the cost is one tuple entry + one upstream injector that emits with the prefix. Existing taxonomy now: PROSE, BLOAT, ORCHESTRATION, BOOT, DAYBOOK, PRECLAIM.
./docs/sprint-memos/7h-40-V5d-operator-bootstrap.codex.log:5629:docs/sprint-memos/7h-39-V4-regex-memo.codex.log:576:/Users/martin/.cursor-daybook-sync/LESSONS.md.bak:383:- 2026-04-26 [enforcement][trend-watch] **Auto-review can detect rotting-pending by reading prior archives; one-shot session metrics miss the slow-growing failure modes.** `agent_review_loop.py` `audit_daybook` now reads the prior 2 entries from `review-archive/` (cheap regex extraction of `pending_journal_items: N` from the markdown), builds a 1-3 element `pending_trend`, and the recommender fires hard `DAYBOOK:` alert when the trend is non-decreasing. Why this matters: a single session with `pending=12` looks indistinguishable from a healthy session that just happens to have queue work; three consecutive sessions with `pending` ≥ each prior is the rot signal. Pattern: per-session metric thresholds catch acute drift; cross-session trends catch chronic drift. Both axes needed — rely on either alone and the other slips.
./docs/sprint-memos/7h-40-V5d-operator-bootstrap.codex.log:5630:docs/sprint-memos/7h-39-V4-regex-memo.codex.log:589:/Users/martin/.cursor-daybook-sync/JOURNAL.md:1637:1. **Pending counter is mechanical, not semantic.** Cited `[orchestration][daybook-gated-sprints]` (LESSON 2026-04-26) as if acknowledgement closed the gap; the regex in `agent_review_loop.py` (checkbox-line OR the literal phrase `P` + `ending decisions`) mechanically scans for a substring. Acknowledgement does not decrement the count.
